AirportFaster — Database Architecture & Entity Relationship Design

Version: 1.0 · Last updated: 2026-05-14 · Status: Draft for founder review

Document Purpose

This document defines the PostgreSQL database architecture for AirportFaster: domains, tables, key columns, relationships, and the rules that protect financial and operational integrity. It is the implementation contract for the Prisma schema. It incorporates the founder decisions logged in DECISIONS.md: AirportFaster is merchant of record (D-006), the customer is charged at checkout (D-007), and the pricing engine supports both fixed price and cost+markup, configurable per airport/service (D-008).

⸻

1. Database Principles

1. PostgreSQL is the single source of truth.
2. All money is stored as integers in minor units (cents/fils) plus an ISO 4217 currency code. No floats for money.
3. Financial and policy data is snapshotted at booking time and never recomputed from live config.
4. All primary keys are UUID v4. All tables carry created_at and updated_at (timestamptz). Soft-deletable entities carry deleted_at.
5. One domain owns its tables; cross-domain reads go through the owning domain's service.
6. Multi-language content lives in dedicated *_translations tables keyed by (parent_id, locale), never as JSON blobs of language.
7. Every status-bearing entity has a companion *_history or *_events table for a full audit trail.
8. Enums are implemented as Postgres enums or constrained lookup tables; never free text.
9. Indexes are defined for every foreign key and every column used in search, filtering, or admin list views.

⸻

2. Domain Map

The schema is organised into the following domains, mirroring the backend modules:

Identity & Access · Airports · Services · Suppliers · Pricing · Availability · Search · Bookings · Payments & Settlements · Refunds · Incidents · Notifications · Flight Data · CMS / SEO · AI Engine · Analytics · Audit · Settings.

⸻

3. Identity & Access Domain

users — internal staff and (future) supplier users. Columns: id, email (unique), password_hash, full_name, status (active/suspended), last_login_at, two_factor_secret (nullable), type (staff/supplier).
roles — id, key (super_admin, operations, customer_support, finance, supplier_manager, content_seo, analyst), name.
permissions — id, key, description.
role_permissions — role_id, permission_id.
user_roles — user_id, role_id.
sessions — id, user_id, token_hash, ip, user_agent, expires_at, revoked_at.
audit_logs — id, actor_user_id, action, entity_type, entity_id, before (jsonb), after (jsonb), ip, created_at. Written for every sensitive action.

Note: customers are NOT in users (D-002, guest checkout). See the Bookings domain.

